On an early morning in September of 1983, Michael Stewart, a 25-year old African-American artist, was confronted by police for drawing graffiti on the walls of the First Avenue L train station. He was beaten, choked with a billy club, hog tied, and delivered to the police station in a comatose state. He died 13 days later. Thereafter, the officers involved were acquitted on all charges. 
Stewart was a great friend to Jean Michel-Basquiat. Basquiat began to express more social justice themes in his work as a result. The Guggenheim currently hosts an exhibit dedicated to his work and others who were enraged by Stewart‚Äôs death. If you the chance, go. It‚Äôs the most powerful exhibit I‚Äôve ever attended. (1) The Death of Michael Stewart (1983)
(2) Irony of a Negro Policeman (1981)
(3) Self-Portrait (1983)
(4) Tuxedo (1982-83)
(5) Untitled (The Sheriff) (1981)
(6) La Hara (1981)
(7) Sketches
(8) Michael Stewart - USA for Africa (1985)

Sentimental post alert:

Anyone who knows me knows...I‚Äôm the world‚Äôs biggest SNL fan (Bill Hader is the greatest cast member ever...we can fight about it). As a kid, I read so many books about what working in Rockefeller Center was like.  All I ever wanted was to work in this building. Big problem: I‚Äôm not even remotely funny. BUT, I still dreamed about it. 
Today, I got to interview with one of the best Entertainment law firms in the world...IN THIS BUILDING. I walked up the red carpet. Rode the elevator. Even met some NBC pages...while shamelessly snapping pics of every corner of every room. 
I have no clue if I‚Äôll get the job. But still. Dream big. Middle school Zach would be psyched right now.

‚ÄúThe National Memorial for Peace and Justice‚Äù was created by EJI. The organization felt that data on American lynching was lacking, and sought to create a comprehensive study. Today, 4,400+ lynchings have been confirmed across the country. The most recent occurred in North Carolina, 1959.

Each ‚Äúblock‚Äù represents a county where a lynching took place. To my family and friends in Volusia County, our ancestors lynched four men.

For those in Orange County, our ancestors lynched 32 men, women, and children on a single day in 1920 alone.

Wonderful meeting with an organization I wish I would have discovered a long time ago. ‚ÄúThe power of just mercy is that it belongs to the undeserving. It‚Äôs when mercy is least expected that it‚Äôs most potent‚Äîstrong enough to break the cycle of victimization and victimhood, retribution and suffering. It has the power to heal the psychic harm and injuries that lead to aggression and violence, abuse of power, mass incarceration.‚Äù

Down in Montgomery to meet with the Equal Justice Initiative. Figured I‚Äôd stop by MLK‚Äôs old church. It‚Äôs basement was the HQ for the Montgomery Bus Boycott. 
The pictured lectern was King‚Äôs. He gave his ‚ÄúHow Long, Not Long‚Äù speech standing behind it. David Oyelowo signed the back after playing him in Selma.
